e government and civil conflict. Easy taxes, they argue, refers not to low taxes, but a tax system with widespread compliance that collects taxes at a reasonable cost from a broad base, like income. And a tolerable administration of justice is about legal infrastructure that can support the enforcement of contracts and property rights in line with the rule of law. The authors show that countries tend to enjoy all three pillars of prosperity when they have evolved cohesive political institutions that promote common interests, guaranteeing the provision of public goods. In line with much historical research, international conflict has also been an important force behind effective states by fostering common interests. The absence of common interests and/or cohesive political institutions can explain the existence of very different development clusters in fragile states that are plagued by poverty, violence, and weak state capacity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBusiness incubators. 0aEconomic development. 0aEconomic policy. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / Theory.2bisacsh  aAdam Smith.  aPillars of Prosperity Index.  abusiness environment.  acivil conflict.  acivil war.  adeveloping countries.  adevelopment assistance.  aeconomic analysis.  aeconomic development.  aeconomic institutions.  aeconomic policy.  aeconomic theory.  aeconomics.  afiscal capacity.  afragile states.  agovernance.  agovernment.  aincome.  ainternational conflict.  ainvestment.  ainvestments.  ajustice.  amicropolitics.  amilitary assistance.  apolitical economics.  apolitical reform.  apolitical stability.  apolitical turnover.  apolitical violence.  apoverty.  aprosperity.  apublic-finance models.  arepression.  arepressive government.  astate building.  astate cap